JEFFERSON CITY — Over the objections of environmental groups and Democrats, Gov. Mike Parson quietly signed Friday a measure stopping local governments from regulating big farms.The legislation, which was the focus of a 12-hour, overnight filibuster in the Missouri Senate this spring, will bar counties from imposing their own pollution-fighting rules on concentrated animal feeding operations, known as CAFOs.The signing came as Parson, who also owns a cattle operation in his hometown of Bolivar, spent the week observing “beef month” with leaders of the Missouri Cattlemen’s Association.

Twenty counties, mostly in the northern half of the state, have sought to regulate large animal operations through local health ordinances. But the new law says counties cannot enact rules more stringent than state standards.Proponents say the local ordinances create a “hodgepodge” of regulations that have stalled expansion of modern agriculture techniques in the state.But opponents — flanked by a vocal statewide network of neighbors affected by the facilities — have said state regulations are lacking, allowing the big farms to run amok and endanger the environment.Passage of the legislation earlier this month came after thousands of Missourians called on lawmakers to drop the legislation.Brian Smith of the Missouri Rural Crisis Center said counties enacted their own rules because state regulators lack the power to protect citizens.“Legislators in Jefferson City and the governor heard loud and clear that the vast majority of Missourians were opposed to Senate Bill 391, yet they chose to side with corporate interests over rural communities,” Smith said after the legislation was approved.
Parson, during a news conference May 17, defended the state’s standards and the Department of Natural Resource’s ability to regulate the large operations.“I’m confident that DNR can handle that to make sure that’s done,” he said. “We’re going to make sure the environment’s protected; we’re going to make sure people’s rights are protected.”Democrats did win a concession during their filibuster: setback requirements for what are known as “export only” CAFOs — operations that ship manure to other farms.
The Democrats were concerned that owners could spray anywhere, with no safeguards for streams or public lands. Some farms near CAFOs welcome the manure, which is a fertilizer that can be offered for free.Parson will highlight the new law when he attends an annual steak fry in Sedalia hosted by the Missouri Cattlemen’s Association on June 9.“We’ve now opened the doors that will allow Missouri to lead the way in meeting a growing world food demand and ensure we keep more agriculture production in our state, strengthening Missouri’s number one industry,” the governor said in a statement Friday.A coalition of farm groups also has praised the law, saying uniform regulations will provide certainty to farmers and ranchers throughout Missouri.“This bill will ensure we use the latest science so that our animals are raised in healthy environments and our water and air remain clean. Missouri farms should be governed by science-based rules and expert oversight, not reactionary fear mongering,” the statement noted.The legislation is Senate Bill 391.


